'Six dead and eight injured,
three of them critically.

02:23.680 --> 02:25.560
'Even at the height
of the war in Iraq,

02:25.600 --> 02:29.600
'British forces did not suffer such
heavy casualties in a single day.'

02:35.520 --> 02:38.080
TELEPHONE RINGS,
TV REPORT CONTINUES

02:38.120 --> 02:42.040
What is it
No, no, we've got it on now.

02:42.080 --> 02:43.560
Mr Reginald Keys?

02:45.400 --> 02:49.120
'..one was wounded
and two vehicles were destroyed.'

02:49.160 --> 02:51.880
I'm Major Potter
and this is Captain Fletcher.

02:51.920 --> 02:53.680
We're from Army Notification.

02:53.720 --> 02:57.520
'..details. In the other,
a patrol of Paras came under fire.

02:57.560 --> 02:59.840
'When a quick reaction force
was sent in to mount

02:59.880 --> 03:03.480
'a helicopter rescue,
they too faced enemy fire.

03:03.520 --> 03:05.680
'We'll be getting reaction here
in a minute

03:05.720 --> 03:08.280
'but first,
Clive Myrie is in Baghdad.'

03:09.720 --> 03:12.880
'Troops from the
1st Battalion Parachute Regiment

03:12.920 --> 03:15.440
'have been based in Southern Iraq
for some time now.

03:15.480 --> 03:19.480
'They were due to return home
at the end of this month.

03:19.520 --> 03:23.320
'In recent weeks, anger has been
rising against British rule...'

03:23.360 --> 03:25.840
TV REPORT AUDIO FADES

03:28.320 --> 03:30.760
SHOUTING,
GUNFIRE

03:37.400 --> 03:39.040
SHE GASPS

03:43.360 --> 03:45.040
SHE WHIMPERS

03:48.600 --> 03:50.360
SHE SOBS

04:02.320 --> 04:03.440
KNOCK ON DOOR

04:03.480 --> 04:04.480
Come in.

04:09.440 --> 04:10.440
At ease.

04:12.560 --> 04:15.440
I've got some bad news,
Sapper Keys. Sir?

04:15.480 --> 04:16.600
About your brother.

04:18.480 --> 04:20.600
Sir? He's been shot dead.

04:27.440 --> 04:28.480
I'm sorry.

04:33.360 --> 04:35.720
What do I do now, sir?

04:35.760 --> 04:38.400
WATER RUNS

04:47.200 --> 04:48.640
DISHES RATTLE

05:02.480 --> 05:04.160
CABINET OPENS

05:20.960 --> 05:23.120
CAR APPROACHES OUTSIDE

05:31.480 --> 05:32.640
It's Richard.

05:45.880 --> 05:47.280
Richard's here, Violet.

05:52.520 --> 05:53.520
You on your own?

05:55.400 --> 05:58.000
They've all been, son.
Been and gone.

06:03.200 --> 06:06.440
Come in. No, thanks, we're just
getting off. Oh, no, you're not.

06:06.480 --> 06:10.600
You're not going all the way
back there without a cup of tea.

06:10.640 --> 06:14.200
Come in. Are you sure? Yeah, go in.

06:43.280 --> 06:45.160
Is Tom coming too?

06:53.320 --> 06:54.920
'My mum died six months ago, '

06:54.960 --> 06:57.200
still thinking Tom was alive.

06:57.240 --> 06:59.360
Sally later said how much
she envied her that.

06:59.400 --> 07:01.440
ENGINE ROARS

07:05.560 --> 07:07.680
MOURNFUL FANFARE PLAYS

07:37.480 --> 07:39.120
QUIET CHATTER

07:40.440 --> 07:42.640
GLASS CLINKS,
CHATTER DIES DOWN

07:42.680 --> 07:46.520
Thank you. Secretary of State,
ladies and gentlemen,

07:46.560 --> 07:50.040
we're going to do this
in order of length of service.

07:50.080 --> 07:53.960
Your name will be called and you'll
go in and sit with your loved one,

07:54.000 --> 07:56.280
for as long as you wish.

07:56.320 --> 08:00.520
First, please, the family of
Sergeant Simon Hamilton-Jewell.

08:32.799 --> 08:36.080
TICKING CLOCK ECHOES

08:36.120 --> 08:38.880
CHATTER RESUMES

09:02.400 --> 09:04.080
WOMAN WHIMPERS

09:11.040 --> 09:13.480
The family of Corporal Paul Long.

09:19.000 --> 09:21.560
TICKING CLOCK ECHOES

09:36.160 --> 09:37.960
DOOR CLOSES

09:51.880 --> 09:54.920
The family
of Lance Corporal Thomas Keys.

10:44.840 --> 10:46.920
HE BREATHES SHARPLY

10:54.480 --> 10:55.800
DOOR CLOSES

10:57.440 --> 11:00.120
There's another couple in after us.

11:00.160 --> 11:03.280
I know.
Let's not stay too long, then.

11:03.320 --> 11:05.800
They stayed for ages.

11:05.840 --> 11:09.760
If we walk out in five minutes,
how's that going to look?

11:09.800 --> 11:11.160
I don't care how it looks.

11:14.560 --> 11:17.000
I need a wee.
Why didn't you go in there?

11:17.040 --> 11:19.520
Cos I didn't want them to say
my name and not be there.

11:22.400 --> 11:23.520
Hmm.

11:24.960 --> 11:26.600
I'm really proud of you, son.

11:28.760 --> 11:31.240
AIRCRAFT ROARS OUTSIDE

12:03.720 --> 12:05.000
Reg?

12:14.280 --> 12:15.480
Right.

12:19.880 --> 12:21.800
A DOOR IS UNLOCKED

12:23.240 --> 12:24.520
DOOR OPENS

14:40.520 --> 14:43.760
COFFIN LID CLICKS AND CREAKS

15:00.840 --> 15:02.920
GUNFIRE RICOCHETS,
SHOUTING ECHOES

15:02.960 --> 15:04.400
LOUD CRUNCH

15:25.320 --> 15:27.320
TWO GUNSHOTS

15:32.360 --> 15:34.560
GUNSHOT

15:36.600 --> 15:38.280
GUNFIRE

16:31.480 --> 16:33.560
MACHINE GUNFIRE
OFFICER: Move back!

16:33.600 --> 16:34.600
GUNSHOT

16:41.560 --> 16:43.760
MACHINE GUNFIRE

16:43.800 --> 16:45.600
SHOUTING

16:48.440 --> 16:50.200
GUNSHOT

16:53.000 --> 16:54.840
SCREAMING,
GUNFIRE CONTINUES

17:01.040 --> 17:02.720
LOUD CRUNCH

18:48.920 --> 18:52.120
There were 31 bullet wounds
to my son's body.

18:52.160 --> 18:55.080
I know, because I counted them
all myself.

18:55.120 --> 18:56.920
DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES

19:02.680 --> 19:04.640
Tell me it's all been a big mistake.

19:07.000 --> 19:08.120
Come in.

19:19.520 --> 19:20.600
Are you sure?

19:23.800 --> 19:24.800
Did he suffer?

19:27.000 --> 19:28.120
One shot.

19:30.240 --> 19:32.000
It would've been instantaneous.

19:48.280 --> 19:49.400
They're here.

19:57.920 --> 20:01.720
I'm Major Bryn Parry Jones, Mr Keys.
Right. Thanks for seeing us.

20:01.760 --> 20:03.240
Oh, no problem.

20:03.280 --> 20:06.440
This is Lance Corporal Joanne
Richardson. How do you do?

20:06.480 --> 20:08.920
And Corporal John Fraser. All right?

20:11.960 --> 20:14.240
Er, I told my wife he didn't suffer.

20:15.400 --> 20:16.760
Just one shot to the head.

20:18.280 --> 20:19.280
Of course.

20:20.480 --> 20:21.880
Well, please come in.

20:29.760 --> 20:31.240
FRONT DOOR CLOSES

20:34.640 --> 20:39.080
This is my wife Sally.
This is Major Bryn Parry Jones.

20:39.120 --> 20:40.680
Oh, hello.

20:40.720 --> 20:43.040
And I've...
I'm sorry, I've forgotten already.

20:43.080 --> 20:45.640
Er, Corporal John Fraser. Oh, hi.

20:45.680 --> 20:47.120
Jo Richardson.

20:47.160 --> 20:48.520
Jo?

20:48.560 --> 20:51.240
Yes. THE Jo?

20:53.280 --> 20:54.600
He mentioned me?

20:54.640 --> 20:56.600
SALLY LAUGHS All the time.

20:58.240 --> 20:59.720
THE Jo, then, yes.

21:03.920 --> 21:06.160
I was very proud of them.

21:06.200 --> 21:09.040
It was a tremendous honour to have
been their commanding officer.

21:09.080 --> 21:11.560
Good men. Really good men.

21:12.840 --> 21:14.400
But even among men like that,

21:14.440 --> 21:16.800
Tom was an exceptional soldier,
Mr Keys.

21:16.840 --> 21:19.880
And, a lot of the time,
funny as well.

21:19.920 --> 21:22.880
Funny and... mischievous.

21:22.920 --> 21:25.880
You'd say that, Corporal? Yes, sir.

21:25.920 --> 21:28.240
Which was great for morale.

21:28.280 --> 21:30.120
Why was he told to stay out there?

21:31.320 --> 21:33.040
It was the end of their stint,
wasn't it?

21:33.080 --> 21:35.880
Tom knew the ropes and we
desperately needed the likes of him

21:35.920 --> 21:37.520
to remain out there
for the handover,

21:37.560 --> 21:40.120
in order to help the new batch
of lads coming out from the UK.

21:40.160 --> 21:43.560
You didn't stay, then? No,
but the CO who took over from me,

21:43.600 --> 21:46.480
Captain Phillips,
he was more than up to the job.

21:46.520 --> 21:47.680
Excellent soldier.

21:49.920 --> 21:52.200
He was four days off
his 21st birthday.

22:03.600 --> 22:05.840
Right, I'll make some more tea,
I think.

22:06.960 --> 22:09.320
Another coffee for you?
Thank you, Mrs Keys.

22:11.000 --> 22:14.640
Jo, would you mind giving me
a hand in the kitchen? Of course.

22:20.320 --> 22:22.000
Do you know why they were attacked?

22:22.040 --> 22:25.400
Well, we're still trying
to get to the bottom of that.

22:25.440 --> 22:27.800
All we know for sure is
a heavily-armed mob

22:27.840 --> 22:30.800
assembled in the town and went off
looking for soldiers to kill.

22:30.840 --> 22:33.960
It was Tom's bad luck... Tea always
tastes better out of a pot,

22:34.000 --> 22:35.680
doesn't it?
SALLY LAUGHS

22:35.720 --> 22:36.840
TEAPOT CLINKS

22:38.080 --> 22:41.120
I mean, there's probably
no real difference, really.

22:43.800 --> 22:46.040
A teabag would probably
taste the same.

22:51.480 --> 22:53.440
Were you... lovers?

23:00.160 --> 23:01.360
Yes.

23:10.280 --> 23:12.040
And when did you last make love?

23:18.360 --> 23:19.720
The, um...

23:24.480 --> 23:25.840
The night before he died.

23:31.960 --> 23:33.960
LOUD SOBBING

23:38.600 --> 23:40.680
SHE WAILS

23:54.480 --> 23:56.320
CABINET OPENS

24:03.040 --> 24:04.200
CORK IS UNSCREWED

24:06.360 --> 24:14.360
♪ Ar ddyrys daith i'r Ganaan fry

24:18.920 --> 24:26.920
♪ Pob gras sydd yn yr Eglwys fawr

24:29.960 --> 24:37.960
♪ Fry yn y nef, neu ar y llawr

24:41.520 --> 24:49.520
♪ Caf feddu'n oll, eu meddu'n un

24:53.000 --> 25:01.000
♪ Wrth feddu d'anian Di dy Hun

25:06.920 --> 25:14.920
♪ Mi lyna'n dawel wrth dy draed

25:18.840 --> 25:26.840
♪ Mi ganaf am rinweddau'r gwaed... ♪

25:30.520 --> 25:38.520
SINGING GETS LOUDER
♪ Mi garia'r groes, mi nofia'r don

25:42.920 --> 25:50.920
♪ Ond cael dy anian dan fy mron. ♪

26:07.120 --> 26:11.080
Five years ago, we gave the Army...

26:11.120 --> 26:14.160
a rather shy, introverted...

26:15.480 --> 26:18.040
..young 16-year-old boy.

26:20.200 --> 26:21.200
Sadly...

26:23.000 --> 26:24.680
..what we see before us today...

26:28.080 --> 26:32.320
..is not how we expected
the Army to return him to us.

26:32.360 --> 26:35.680
'Not the homecoming
we had planned for Tom.'

26:35.720 --> 26:38.600
SEAGULLS CALL,
GUNFIRE ECHOES

26:42.480 --> 26:44.400
GUNFIRE ECHOES

26:44.440 --> 26:46.120
GUNS ARE RELOADED

26:49.520 --> 26:51.120
GUNFIRE ECHOES

26:54.160 --> 26:56.560
BUZZ OF CONVERSATION

26:56.600 --> 26:59.880
Goodbye, then.
You take care. Thank you.

27:07.520 --> 27:08.760
Sorry.

27:13.640 --> 27:18.240
How are you? OK.I need to
tell you something, Mr Keys.

27:18.280 --> 27:21.040
It might come as a bit
of a surprise. Yes?

27:29.520 --> 27:33.240
A few weeks before they were killed,
the lads were descaled.

27:33.280 --> 27:36.160
Descaled? It's Army jargon
for removing equipment -

27:36.200 --> 27:39.640
grenades, flares and so on.
It's just so the new lads coming in

27:39.680 --> 27:41.400
have everything they need.

27:41.440 --> 27:46.120
Well, that's no surprise.
It seems reasonable, in fact.

27:48.480 --> 27:49.600
Thanks.

27:55.800 --> 27:57.000
Grenades and flares?

27:59.440 --> 28:00.440
Yes.

28:03.240 --> 28:04.240
Anything else?

28:05.960 --> 28:06.960
Some ammo.

28:08.760 --> 28:09.760
Some?

28:11.840 --> 28:13.440
They only had 50 rounds each.

28:15.440 --> 28:16.880
50?! Yes.

28:18.280 --> 28:20.440
In Majar al

28:20.480 --> 28:21.800
Yes.

28:21.840 --> 28:24.400
You knew this at the time?

28:24.440 --> 28:28.240
Yes. But you still came home
and left them there? Yes.

28:32.800 --> 28:34.920
Why are you telling me this now?

28:34.960 --> 28:38.560
The papers have got hold of it.
They're running the story.

28:38.600 --> 28:40.160
Oh, so you're telling me this now,

28:40.200 --> 28:42.000
because you've GOT
to tell me this now?

28:42.040 --> 28:44.680
No.
I am telling you this now, because

28:44.720 --> 28:47.760
it's easier to hear it from me
than to read it in the tabloids.

28:50.640 --> 28:53.880
We're thinking of you and the other
families, Mr Keys, that's all.

28:53.920 --> 28:55.280
Uh-huh.

28:58.640 --> 29:00.720
What else was taken off them?

29:03.160 --> 29:04.240
Morphine.

29:05.760 --> 29:06.760
Anything else?

29:09.160 --> 29:12.640
A satellite phone. Well, that's what
the papers are saying, but they were

29:12.680 --> 29:15.560
never given a satellite phone.
They had a clansman radio.

29:15.600 --> 29:19.000
But a clansman is
bolted to the vehicle.

29:23.680 --> 29:24.920
Yes.

29:26.320 --> 29:28.800
Away from the vehicle,
what did they have?

29:35.600 --> 29:37.960
Away from the vehicle,
what did they have?

29:42.680 --> 29:43.680
Nothing.

29:59.240 --> 30:00.840
BIRDS CALL

30:09.280 --> 30:11.920
There were dozens
of bullet wounds to his body.

30:13.840 --> 30:15.040
I heard them talking.

30:17.440 --> 30:18.440
You said one.

30:20.440 --> 30:21.520
One shot to the head.

30:27.440 --> 30:30.680
It's what you wanted to hear.
I want to hear the truth, Reg.

30:42.240 --> 30:44.080
They only had 50 rounds each.

30:50.200 --> 30:51.360
No radio.

31:03.960 --> 31:06.000
SHE WHIMPERS

31:18.320 --> 31:21.040
I don't want you going
back to the Army, Richard.

31:23.120 --> 31:25.600
Look, if I leave the Army, Mum,
what have I got?

31:25.640 --> 31:27.600
There's nothing here.

31:27.640 --> 31:30.720
Besides, Tom got killed.
They'll look after me.

31:33.440 --> 31:35.720
They don't want two
from the same family.

32:39.440 --> 32:42.080
'The Prime Minister
hasn't smiled like this

32:42.120 --> 32:44.760
'for a long time. But it's the
troubles at home that have been

32:44.800 --> 32:46.280
'the very making of him over here.

32:46.320 --> 32:51.240
'America adores his unwavering
loyalty and this is his reward.

32:51.280 --> 32:53.240
'Mr Speaker, the Prime Minister

32:53.280 --> 32:57.920
'of the United Kingdom of
Great Britain and Northern Ireland.'

32:57.960 --> 32:59.320
CHEERING

33:00.800 --> 33:03.720
'Only very few foreigners and
two other Britons have been given

33:03.760 --> 33:07.240
'the honour of addressing
a joint session of Congress.

33:07.280 --> 33:10.400
'The first was Winston Churchill,
who did it three times,

33:10.440 --> 33:12.680
'twice during the Second World War.

33:12.720 --> 33:15.600
'The last was Margaret Thatcher
at the height of the Cold War.'

33:27.960 --> 33:33.400
'I'm deeply touched by that warm
and generous welcome that's...

33:35.600 --> 33:38.880
'..more than I deserve and more than
I'm used to, quite frankly...'

33:38.920 --> 33:40.360
LAUGHTER

33:41.440 --> 33:44.400
'And...'
APPLAUSE AND CHEERING

33:48.520 --> 33:51.440
'..you, like me,
know who the real heroes are.

33:53.040 --> 33:57.040
'Those brave servicemen
and women, yours and ours,

33:57.080 --> 34:01.040
'who fought the war
and risk their lives still.

34:01.080 --> 34:03.560
'And our tribute to them
should be measured...'

34:03.600 --> 34:05.840
FRONT DOOR OPENS
'..in this way.

34:05.880 --> 34:08.880
CAR KEYS RATTLE
'By showing them and their families

34:08.920 --> 34:11.800
'that they did not strive
or die in vain.

34:11.840 --> 34:14.719
'But that, through their sacrifice,

34:14.760 --> 34:20.760
'future generations can live in
greater peace, prosperity and hope.

34:20.800 --> 34:24.159
'Let me also express my gratitude
to President Bush.

34:24.199 --> 34:27.239
'Through the troubled times,
since September the 11th

34:27.280 --> 34:33.040
'changed our world,
we have been allies and friends.

34:33.080 --> 34:35.920
'Thank you, Mr President...'
You're killing yourself.

34:35.960 --> 34:37.719
APPLAUSE ON TV

34:39.040 --> 34:40.239
Good.

34:48.040 --> 34:49.760
Turn it off.

34:49.800 --> 34:51.760
If it hurts so much, just...

34:53.679 --> 34:54.800
..turn it off.

34:57.600 --> 34:59.480
Or you need the pain.

34:59.520 --> 35:01.600
It gives you a good excuse
to do that.

35:01.640 --> 35:04.440
'I'm being told that the first
Congressional Gold Medal was

35:04.480 --> 35:06.880
'awarded to George Washington
for what Congress called

35:06.920 --> 35:08.840
'his "wise and spirited conduct"

35:08.880 --> 35:11.520
'in getting rid of the British
out of Boston.'

35:11.560 --> 35:13.920
LAUGHTER ON TV

35:13.960 --> 35:15.680
You'd leave me all alone, would you?

35:15.720 --> 35:18.480
CHEERING ON TV

35:18.520 --> 35:21.320
Leave me to go through
all this on my own?

35:21.360 --> 35:22.800
How selfish is that?

35:25.840 --> 35:26.840
What about Tom?

35:29.800 --> 35:32.840
If he was alive, you'd think
he'd want to see you like this?

35:32.880 --> 35:36.720
'..was kind enough to show me
the fireplace where, in 1814,

35:36.760 --> 35:39.800
'the British had burnt
the Congress Library.

35:39.840 --> 35:42.920
'I know this is kind of late,
but sorry.'

35:42.960 --> 35:44.720
LAUGHTER

35:44.760 --> 35:46.520
APPLAUSE

35:50.000 --> 35:51.400
I saw that teacher today.

35:52.840 --> 35:53.840
What teacher?

36:03.000 --> 36:06.480
The one who said that Tom
was too good for the Army.

36:06.520 --> 36:10.200
'But though
we love freedom, others don't...'

36:10.240 --> 36:12.120
I wanted to say...

36:12.160 --> 36:13.760
"I agree with you, Mr Talbot,

36:13.800 --> 36:17.000
"I didn't want him
anywhere near the Army.

36:17.040 --> 36:18.720
"But his dad was all for it."

36:18.760 --> 36:21.880
'..Western values,
that Afghan women were..."

36:21.920 --> 36:25.360
Well, you said nothing
at the time. What was the point?

36:25.400 --> 36:29.000
He was always going to do what
his dad wanted him to do, wasn't he?

36:33.800 --> 36:37.280
You said you were proud of him.
He's lying there in his coffin

36:37.320 --> 36:39.480
and you're telling him
you're proud of him.

36:39.520 --> 36:41.560
Proud of what?

36:41.600 --> 36:43.560
You're proud of them
when they do something,

36:43.600 --> 36:45.800
when they achieve something.

36:45.840 --> 36:47.800
What's he done?

36:47.840 --> 36:48.960
What's he achieved?

36:51.280 --> 36:54.240
He's got himself
shot to bits in some shit-hole

36:54.280 --> 36:55.760
in the middle of the desert!

36:57.560 --> 36:59.120
And all for nothing!

37:00.880 --> 37:02.960
'Actually...'For nothing.

37:03.000 --> 37:06.040
'..you know, my middle son was
studying 18th-century history

37:06.080 --> 37:08.120
'and the American War
of Independence

37:08.160 --> 37:11.720
'and he said to me the other day,
"You know Lord North, Dad?

37:11.760 --> 37:15.320
' "He was the British Prime Minister
who lost us America.

37:15.360 --> 37:17.960
' "So just think,
however many mistakes you'll make,

37:18.000 --> 37:19.760
' "you'll never
make one that bad." '

37:19.800 --> 37:21.040
LAUGHTER

37:21.080 --> 37:23.800
And we should pray too for those

37:23.840 --> 37:26.560
who have to keep on
at the task of rebuilding,

37:26.600 --> 37:29.600
when the dramas
of conflict have faded,

37:29.640 --> 37:33.360
for our leaders,
here and in the United States.

37:33.400 --> 37:38.840
We have made ourselves accountable
for peace and justice in Iraq.

37:40.280 --> 37:44.720
And leaders and people alike
will be called to account for it.

37:47.760 --> 37:50.720
I'd like to speak
to the Prime Minister, please.

37:50.760 --> 37:55.000
Sorry? I said, "I'd like to speak
to the Prime Minister, please."

37:55.040 --> 37:57.720
It's Mr Keys, isn't it? Yes.

37:57.760 --> 38:00.600
Um, you've already spoken to him,
haven't you?

38:00.640 --> 38:02.560
Yeah, for about five seconds.

38:02.600 --> 38:05.560
And he was led away, or
he allowed himself to be led away.

38:05.600 --> 38:08.200
I'd like to speak to him properly,
please. I'm really sorry,

38:08.240 --> 38:11.200
but I don't think that's going
to be possible. He's extremely busy.

38:11.240 --> 38:12.480
I can wait.

38:16.400 --> 38:18.480
What is it you'd like
to speak to him about?

38:18.520 --> 38:21.280
Well, my son was killed in Iraq -
there's a clue.

38:21.320 --> 38:23.800
Well, I'm very sorry about that,
Mr Keys, and if you'd like

38:23.840 --> 38:26.320
to give me a message, I can pass
it on to the Prime Minister.

38:26.360 --> 38:28.000
I'm sure he'll get back in touch.

38:28.040 --> 38:29.520
OK.

38:29.560 --> 38:35.080
A 500-strong mob, armed to
the teeth, baying for blood,

38:35.120 --> 38:40.280
came after my son
and he had 50 bullets and no radio.

38:40.320 --> 38:43.600
Now, I can accept that, just about.

38:43.640 --> 38:46.960
But if I find out this war
didn't have to be fought,

38:47.000 --> 38:48.480
and he died for nothing...

38:50.000 --> 38:52.800
..I will never accept that,
I will never let that lie.

38:52.840 --> 38:57.120
Mr Keys, these weapons of
mass destruction will be found.

38:58.400 --> 38:59.760
I assure you of that.

39:01.840 --> 39:04.640
BBC NEWS THEME PLAYS

39:09.720 --> 39:13.200
'Good evening. The main argument
for invading Iraq -

39:13.240 --> 39:15.880
'that Saddam Hussein had
weapons of mass destruction -

39:15.920 --> 39:19.600
'has been laid to rest by
the leading US arms inspector.

39:19.640 --> 39:22.280
'Charles Duelfer,
head of the Iraq Survey Group,

39:22.320 --> 39:25.040
'published his long-awaited
report this evening.

39:25.080 --> 39:27.520
'He said that Saddam
did not have any chemical

39:27.560 --> 39:31.040
'or biological stockpiles
when the war began last year.'

39:31.080 --> 39:32.720
CLOCK STRIKES

40:01.280 --> 40:03.560
CAMERAS CLICK Mr Keys?

40:03.600 --> 40:06.720
I'm still waiting to talk to Tony.

40:06.760 --> 40:08.360
Still very busy, I'm afraid.

40:10.400 --> 40:12.240
We have a petition.

40:12.280 --> 40:14.360
I'll see that he gets it.

40:14.400 --> 40:16.600
We're all people
who've lost sons in Iraq.

40:16.640 --> 40:18.120
We'd like to give him it ourselves.

40:18.160 --> 40:20.160
It's just not going to be possible,
I'm afraid.

40:20.200 --> 40:23.520
People who give a few grand to
the party, they get to talk to him.

40:23.560 --> 40:26.080
We've given a lot more than that -
we've given our sons.

40:26.120 --> 40:29.000
I will tell the Prime Minister that
you came and I will see that he gets

40:29.040 --> 40:32.960
your petition and, um... Well, I
thank you all very much for coming.

40:44.360 --> 40:45.640
DOOR CLOSES

41:03.840 --> 41:06.760
'..delegates,
if they wish to, prioritise Iraq

41:06.800 --> 41:09.840
'over the health service, over
education, over employment matters,

41:09.880 --> 41:11.600
'over other issues.
That's their right.

41:11.640 --> 41:13.640
'You know, hunting and Iraq
are fringe issues

41:13.680 --> 41:15.800
'as far as
this conference is concerned...'

41:15.840 --> 41:18.680
'Well, it's their
right to choose...'

41:18.720 --> 41:20.440
It can't fail.

41:20.480 --> 41:21.800
See?

41:21.840 --> 41:25.680
This stops it, see?
Why are you doing it?

41:25.720 --> 41:27.680
Tony bloody Blair.

41:27.720 --> 41:31.720
'..a major debate. But there is,
there is a debate on Thursday...'

42:05.600 --> 42:08.760
Have you seen this, Sapper Keys?
Sir!

42:08.800 --> 42:11.000
It's a life hanging
in the balance, sir.

42:11.040 --> 42:14.320
As hundreds of thousands of other
lives hang in the balance, sir.

42:14.360 --> 42:17.200
While the Prime Minister
won't even talk about it, sir.

42:17.240 --> 42:18.760
Is he mad?

42:18.800 --> 42:20.320
Fuming, sir.

42:23.480 --> 42:25.480
So you're not suicidal at all, then?

42:25.520 --> 42:27.440
No, no. No.

42:29.960 --> 42:31.120
I just miss my son.

42:35.400 --> 42:36.600
I just miss him.

42:39.440 --> 42:41.000
I miss him so much.

42:42.960 --> 42:44.280
HE SNIFFS

42:44.320 --> 42:47.880
MALE VOICE CHOIR SINGS

43:02.240 --> 43:04.320
SINGING CONTINUES

43:28.320 --> 43:31.400
LOUD SINGING

43:37.160 --> 43:40.040
SINGING STOPS GRADUALLY

43:46.080 --> 43:49.760
I'd join you, lads, but, er,
my throat's a bit sore.

43:49.800 --> 43:52.520
LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE

44:09.840 --> 44:12.080
Reg? I'm Felicity Arbuthnot.

44:12.120 --> 44:13.200
We're just up here.

44:14.360 --> 44:15.640
Brilliant, by the way.

44:39.560 --> 44:40.680
Reg Keys, everyone.

44:41.720 --> 44:42.720
Please, Reg.

44:46.240 --> 44:48.480
What can I do for you?

44:48.520 --> 44:53.920
We'd like you to take on Tony Blair
at the next general election.

44:57.960 --> 45:00.880
'..but the fact that
their economic and health

45:00.920 --> 45:05.480
'and education plans are exactly
the ones they rejected in 1997.

45:05.520 --> 45:09.000
'I think, when they do that,
that, yes, I'll be very happy

45:09.040 --> 45:12.960
'that people compare the choice
between their record and ours,

45:13.000 --> 45:15.920
'between our future programme
and theirs.

45:15.960 --> 45:17.400
SHOUTS OF AGREEMENT

45:17.440 --> 45:19.560
'Well, he
talks about his record.

45:19.600 --> 45:22.800
'Let's look at his record.
I'll tell him about his record.

45:22.840 --> 45:28.440
'Taxes UP! OTHERS: Up!
Crime UP! Up! Immigration UP! Up!'

45:28.480 --> 45:30.480
MOBILE PHONE BEEPS
'Waiting times UP! Up!

45:30.520 --> 45:33.960
'MRSA UP! Up! Truancy UP! Up!

45:34.000 --> 45:36.120
'And let's have a look
at what's gone down.

45:36.160 --> 45:39.720
'Take home pay DOWN! Down!
Pensions DOWN.Down!'

45:39.760 --> 45:41.200
Hi, it's Reg.

45:42.360 --> 45:45.440
Are you watching
Prime Minister's Questions?

45:45.480 --> 45:48.680
Talk about "don't mention the war".
'Let me just remind him...'

45:48.720 --> 45:50.520
The answer's yes.

45:50.560 --> 45:51.560
I'll do it.

45:52.960 --> 45:54.320
I'm going to take him on.

45:55.880 --> 45:57.800
Take who on?

45:57.840 --> 46:01.880
Blair. I'm going to stand for
Parliament, in his constituency.

46:03.280 --> 46:04.840
REG SIGHS

46:07.240 --> 46:09.000
Where's that?

46:09.040 --> 46:10.040
Sedgefield.

46:13.120 --> 46:14.960
Where's Sedgefield?

46:15.000 --> 46:16.760
It's the North East.

46:20.760 --> 46:23.040
Is that where he's from? No.

46:23.080 --> 46:24.520
No, no.

46:24.560 --> 46:25.640
Oh.

46:28.920 --> 46:30.440
Why?

46:30.480 --> 46:31.760
Because he lied. Oh!

46:31.800 --> 46:34.680
Because he took us to war on a lie!
Reg, you've got nothing to prove!

46:34.720 --> 46:38.120
What does that mean? Everybody knows
how much you loved him.

46:38.160 --> 46:41.200
No, it's not that. Well, then,
what is it? It's not Tom.

46:43.720 --> 46:47.920
I think I could find it in me,
somewhere deep within me,

46:47.960 --> 46:50.760
to forgive that bastard
for what he did to Tom...

46:52.800 --> 46:55.640
..but I'll never forgive him
for what he did to you.

47:01.600 --> 47:02.760
Yeah.

47:09.960 --> 47:13.560
It might make things
a bit awkward for you. How?

47:13.600 --> 47:16.160
Well, you're in the Army!
I can't be the first soldier to

47:16.200 --> 47:19.160
have a dad standing for Parliament.
They won't see it like that,

47:19.200 --> 47:22.200
but as your dad's making problems
for the Prime Minister of Britain.

47:22.240 --> 47:23.760
So? He's made enough for us.

47:26.720 --> 47:28.480
Could you beat him?

47:28.520 --> 47:29.520
Why not?

47:31.640 --> 47:33.840
Hey, that's better than
bumping him off.

47:33.880 --> 47:35.320
Yeah.

47:35.360 --> 47:37.800
To Tom. To Tom.

47:37.840 --> 47:40.880
Tony Blair was more than happy to go

47:40.920 --> 47:44.720
2,000 miles across the Atlantic
to talk to his American friends,

47:44.760 --> 47:48.280
but not prepared to walk as far
as his own doorstep to talk to us.

47:49.520 --> 47:51.760
People whose sons
had died in that war.

47:51.800 --> 47:54.960
He's more than happy to talk about
democracy for the people in Iraq,

47:55.000 --> 47:58.320
but not prepared to listen to us,
his own people,

47:58.360 --> 48:02.280
standing there, shivering,
grieving on his own doorstep.

48:10.640 --> 48:12.160
Reg.

48:12.200 --> 48:14.120
Yes?

48:14.160 --> 48:15.760
Ah.

48:15.800 --> 48:17.280
Whisky!

48:20.000 --> 48:22.360
Well,
not that it's any of your business,

48:22.400 --> 48:26.480
but I've been campaigning all day
and I felt I deserved it.

48:26.520 --> 48:28.880
You haven't been campaigning.

48:28.920 --> 48:30.640
I beg your pardon?

48:30.680 --> 48:34.320
Spouting outside Tesco's with
three people and a dog listening?

48:34.360 --> 48:36.360
That's not campaigning.

48:36.400 --> 48:39.680
And you didn't feel like you
deserved that whisky either.

48:39.720 --> 48:42.440
You felt like you needed it.

48:42.480 --> 48:44.400
Nice talking to you.

48:44.440 --> 48:46.400
We spoke on the phone.

48:46.440 --> 48:47.920
I'm Bob Clay.

48:49.440 --> 48:50.680
Oh.

48:51.880 --> 48:54.400
How do you do, Bob?
How do you do, Reg?

48:55.840 --> 49:01.720
So, do you still want my help?
Yes. Then can I be frank?

49:01.760 --> 49:03.800
Well, what have you been so far?

49:03.840 --> 49:06.600
If we're going to do this,
we do it properly.

49:06.640 --> 49:09.280
I'm not here to cause
a bit of mischief, I'm here to win.

49:09.320 --> 49:12.360
And you win by talking to
as many voters as possible.

49:12.400 --> 49:15.800
That means knocking on doors,
morning, noon and night.

49:15.840 --> 49:17.720
That means you'll hardly
see your missus

49:17.760 --> 49:19.200
between now and election night.

49:19.240 --> 49:22.320
And that means, halfway through
this campaign, you'll hate my guts!

49:22.360 --> 49:26.240
But by the end of it,
you'll be shaking my hand.

49:26.280 --> 49:28.720
So, are you up for that?

49:28.760 --> 49:31.000
Can Reg be frank now, Bob? Yeah.

49:32.440 --> 49:36.560
You hate Tony Blair. That's why
you're here. Yes? Oh, yeah.

49:36.600 --> 49:43.120
Well, I loved my son. My love of my
son will keep me going a lot longer

49:43.160 --> 49:45.160
than your hatred
of Tony bloody Blair.

49:49.120 --> 49:52.040
Have you any skeletons
in the closet, Reg? None.

49:52.080 --> 49:54.600
Cos they'll find them if you have.
None whatsoever.

49:55.760 --> 49:58.720
Right, so you do this one,
I'll do next door

49:58.760 --> 50:02.640
and then we'll just leapfrog
each other up the street.

50:02.680 --> 50:04.360
It'll seem a little
strange at first,

50:04.400 --> 50:07.400
but after you've done three or four,
you'll be like falling off a log.

50:07.440 --> 50:09.960
I'm shitting myself. Eh!
These are working class people.

50:10.000 --> 50:11.360
They'll love you for it.

50:15.120 --> 50:17.920
DOORBELLS RING

50:19.880 --> 50:21.680
Hello, sir.

50:21.720 --> 50:23.680
I'm Reg Keys.

50:23.720 --> 50:27.000
My son Tom was one of six
military policeman killed in Iraq.

50:27.040 --> 50:29.160
Reg Keys? Yes.

50:29.200 --> 50:31.720
May I shake your hand, Mr Keys?

50:31.760 --> 50:34.160
And, yes, you can count on me vote.

50:35.640 --> 50:36.680
Thank you.

50:36.720 --> 50:38.840
Tony Blair sent them
there on a falsehood, sir.

50:38.880 --> 50:41.240
I wonder if we could count
on your vote. Er, yeah.

50:41.280 --> 50:43.440
Thank you. OK, no problem.

50:46.120 --> 50:49.320
Hello, I'm Martin Bell,
former BBC war correspondent,

50:49.360 --> 50:51.720
and I'm campaigning
on behalf of Reg Keys,

50:51.760 --> 50:53.560
whose son Tom died in Iraq.

50:54.840 --> 50:58.520
Oh, hello, I'm sorry to bother you.
I'm Frederick Forsyth, the novelist.

50:58.560 --> 51:01.840
I'm helping Reg Keys
in his campaign against Tony Blair,

51:01.880 --> 51:03.680
the man who took us to war in a lie,

51:03.720 --> 51:05.920
and I was hoping
we could count on your vote.

51:05.960 --> 51:10.320
No.Um, may I ask why not?
You don't want to know why.

51:10.360 --> 51:12.080
I do. You don't.

51:13.600 --> 51:16.560
This is a howl of pain,
Mr Keys, all this.

51:16.600 --> 51:19.520
It's just a howl of pain. Please
tell me why you won't vote for me.

51:19.560 --> 51:21.880
Reg?
I gave my son two rules, Mr Keys.

51:21.920 --> 51:23.640
One - you don't buy a motorbike.

51:23.680 --> 51:25.600
Two - you don't join
the British Army.

51:25.640 --> 51:28.400
Both could get you killed. My son...
You should've done the same.

51:28.440 --> 51:30.680
My son didn't die
because he joined the Army... Reg?

51:30.720 --> 51:32.960
My son died because the Army
sent him into a hellhole

51:33.000 --> 51:34.320
with 50 bullets and no radio.

51:34.360 --> 51:37.400
It's what the Army does, Mr Keys -
it lets its soldiers down.

51:37.440 --> 51:40.840
And not to expect to be let down's a
bit naive, and who wants a naive MP?

51:40.880 --> 51:43.560
Is it naive to expect
the Prime Minister to tell the truth

51:43.600 --> 51:45.720
when he sends his soldiers...?
He's a politician!

51:45.760 --> 51:48.160
I don't accept what you say...
He's a politician!

51:48.200 --> 51:50.640
It's about the Army and these men...
You're wanted, Reg!

51:50.680 --> 51:54.400
The Prime Minister can lie sending soldiers
to war! I'm sorry we don't see eye to eye.

51:54.440 --> 51:57.160
Excuse us, we've a lot of people...
I'm talking! By all means.

51:57.200 --> 51:59.320
Some want to speak to Reg
personally. I'm talking!

51:59.360 --> 52:00.840
You do not argue with them!

52:00.880 --> 52:04.120
"I'm very sorry we don't see eye to
eye on this matter, sir," and walk!

52:04.160 --> 52:05.840
You know what you've just achieved?

52:05.880 --> 52:08.360
He's absolutely fucking determined
to vote AGAINST you!

52:08.400 --> 52:09.680
It's a waste of time and energy

52:09.720 --> 52:11.760
and absolutely fucking
counter-productive!

52:11.800 --> 52:14.680
Now, go and join Martin!
Reg? This is Trevor Johnson.

52:14.720 --> 52:16.920
How do you do?
How do you do, Mr Johnson?

52:16.960 --> 52:19.720
RAIN PATTERS OUTSIDE
How are you?

52:19.760 --> 52:21.280
'Fine.'

52:21.320 --> 52:23.200
You OK?'I'm fine.

52:24.560 --> 52:27.160
SHE SWALLOWS
'Are you drinking?'

52:28.320 --> 52:30.880
Tea. Are you eating?'Yeah.'

52:32.120 --> 52:35.800
What?'I said yes.'
No, what are you eating?

52:35.840 --> 52:38.720
Oh, a sandwich.
'Well, that's not enough!'

52:38.760 --> 52:42.040
It's fine. 'That's not -
you need some proper food!'

52:42.080 --> 52:43.680
Well, it's only for tonight.

52:47.600 --> 52:48.800
Are you coping, then?

52:50.520 --> 52:51.800
'More than coping.'

52:51.840 --> 52:53.600
'Are you sure?'

52:54.960 --> 52:55.960
Positive.

52:59.240 --> 53:01.520
Enjoying the peace and quiet,
actually.

53:02.800 --> 53:06.240
I'll be home the weekend.
We'll go to the garden centre.

53:08.000 --> 53:09.320
'Have lunch there.'

53:11.720 --> 53:12.800
Yeah.

53:16.000 --> 53:18.080
'Bye, love.' Bye, love.

53:19.480 --> 53:20.680
'Bye.' Bye.

53:38.800 --> 53:41.120
9 o'clock in the morning,
till 7.30 at night.

53:41.160 --> 53:43.920
7.30, because Bob says
you don't knock on the door

53:43.960 --> 53:47.080
once Coronation Street's started,
or EastEnders.

53:47.120 --> 53:49.680
We always vote for Mr Blair here.

53:49.720 --> 53:53.840
Always vote for Mr Blair?
Yes, we always vote for Tony.

53:53.880 --> 53:55.000
Right.

53:55.040 --> 53:58.320
'Then it's back to the hotel
for a phone call with Sally.'

53:58.360 --> 54:02.080
Then, er,
meet Bob again for a debrief.

54:02.120 --> 54:04.720
Day after day. Week after week.

54:04.760 --> 54:07.960
Reg and I are visiting all
the betting shops in Sedgefield

54:08.000 --> 54:11.720
and we're telling everyone in there
to back Reg Keys and vote for him.

54:11.760 --> 54:13.640
When you back a horse,
what can you do

54:13.680 --> 54:16.720
to affect the running of that
horse, hmm? Absolutely nothing.

54:16.760 --> 54:20.160
You are totally at the mercy
of the horse and jockey.

54:20.200 --> 54:24.040
But back Reg Keys,
ladies and gentlemen,

54:24.080 --> 54:27.400
and there is something you can do -
you can vote for the bugger!

54:27.440 --> 54:30.320
Currently, he is 200-1.

54:30.360 --> 54:33.680
In an hour, he'll be 100-1.
In two hours, he'll be 50-1.

54:33.720 --> 54:35.280
In three hours, he'll be 20-1.

54:35.320 --> 54:37.960
In four hours, he'll be down to tens
and, by the end of the day,

54:38.000 --> 54:39.680
you'll be lucky to get even money.

54:39.720 --> 54:42.840
So, ladies and gentlemen,
backed Reg Keys now!

54:42.880 --> 54:43.880
CHEERING

54:43.920 --> 54:47.200
I was in Downing Street handing in
a petition. I couldn't help noticing

54:47.240 --> 54:49.600
how well equipped
their policemen were there.

54:49.640 --> 54:54.800
They had pistols, automatic
machine guns, radios, earpieces.

54:54.840 --> 54:57.400
Tony Blair gets more protection
in the middle of London

54:57.440 --> 54:58.960
than our boys get in a warzone.

55:06.840 --> 55:10.360
Hello again, Mr Keys.
We've got to stop meeting like this.

55:10.400 --> 55:12.680
The Prime Minister's not in,
I'm afraid.

55:14.920 --> 55:16.840
Why all this?

55:16.880 --> 55:19.600
Would you like me
to give him a message? Yes.

55:19.640 --> 55:25.280
He's invited to a televised debate -
me, him, anyone else he fancies.

55:25.320 --> 55:28.080
That's not going to happen,
I'm afraid.

55:28.120 --> 55:30.280
Why not?

55:30.320 --> 55:32.000
It's just not going to happen.

55:33.920 --> 55:35.440
I will have my say.

55:35.480 --> 55:37.440
I'll look forward to that, Mr Keys.

55:42.600 --> 55:45.120
Modern trains I'm talking about.
Not old ones, modern ones.

55:45.160 --> 55:47.480
I go in for a piss, right?
Not a shit, just a piss,

55:47.520 --> 55:49.680
but you've still got
to flush it, haven't you?

55:49.720 --> 55:51.600
But the flash is behind the seat,
isn't it?

55:51.640 --> 55:54.240
So you put the seat down and now
you've touched a lavatory seat,

